Charles Sirleaf, ex-governor of Central Bank and son of the former President of Liberia, has been charged with overprinting currency the equivalent of over $100 million U.S. dollars.

Sirleaf's indictment follows months of investigation into a container of Liberian banknotes that went missing last year. In February, a business intelligence firm released a report that connected the missing money to the surplus of currency that was printed at Central Bank after the Liberian government approved the printing of $5 billion.

