A joint federal lawsuit was filed in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia against the U.S. Department of Justice and the FBI for their failure to perform congressionally sanctioned protocol, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190327180223/http://www.courthousenews.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/911-commission.pdf">when</a> they were charged with assessing evidence related to the  9/11 attacks.

The complaint cites the mistakes of the FBI and its 9/11 Review Commission when they assessed crucial 9/11 evidence. The joint lawsuit is requesting claims for declaratory and injunctive relief under the Administrative Procedure Act. "A review of the 2015 FBI 9/11 Review Commission Report on its face indicates that the steps taken by the 9/11 Review Commission in doing its work in response to the mandate from Congress did not include reviewing and developing a written assessment of the three
“tranches” of FBI documents recently referenced by the DOJ in the lawsuit by the 9/11 family members against the Saudis." Specifically, the Review Commission is being charged with not disclosing pre-placed explosives, which were already in existence on the World Trade Center sites.

The relief requested by the plaintiffs involves a new assessment of any evidence known to the FBI that was not disclosed by the original 9/11 commission. The claim for relief also <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190327180223/http://www.courthousenews.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/911-commission.pdf">requires</a> defendants to make good faith efforts toward recovering any evidence that was destroyed or lost during the original investigation. This lawsuit represents a push towards transparency and accountability by the government towards it's citizens.

